('business:1-3-business-ownership:exam:861c5290', 'business', 'business:1-3-business-ownership', '1.3 Business Ownership', 'exam', 'mcq', 1, '{"num": "Q2", "question": "What is a disadvantage of being a sole trader?", "options": ["Can only have one employee", "Cannot share business ownership", "Legally required to produce a business plan", "Must pay corporation tax"], "hint": "Think about what ''sole'' actually means — and what that limits the owner from doing.", "starter": "The correct answer is..."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 1, "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\"><h5>Answer: B — Cannot share business ownership</h5>\n<p><strong>Why B is correct:</strong> By definition, a sole trader has one owner. This limits the ability to raise capital and means all risks and responsibilities fall entirely on one person.</p>\n<p><strong>Why the others are wrong:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>A — Wrong:</strong> Sole traders CAN employ more than one person. ''Sole'' means one owner, not one worker.</li>\n<li><strong>C — Wrong:</strong> There is no legal requirement for a sole trader to produce a business plan.</li>\n<li><strong>D — Wrong:</strong> Sole traders pay Income Tax on their profits, not corporation tax. Corporation tax is paid by limited companies only.</li>\n</ul></div>", "modelAnswer": ""}'::jsonb),
('business:1-3-business-ownership:exam:32a4005e', 'business', 'business:1-3-business-ownership', '1.3 Business Ownership', 'exam', 'mcq', 1, '{"num": "Q3", "question": "Limited liability protects:", "options": ["Business owners", "Customers", "Suppliers", "The local community"], "hint": "Limited liability is about protecting one specific group of people from losing personal wealth when a company cannot pay its debts.", "starter": "The correct answer is..."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\"><h5>Answer: A — Business owners</h5>\n<p><strong>Why A is correct:</strong> Limited liability is a legal protection for the owners (shareholders) of a company. It limits their personal financial responsibility to the amount originally invested.</p>\n<p><strong>Why the others are wrong:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>B — Wrong:</strong> Customers are protected by consumer law, not limited liability.</li>\n<li><strong>C — Wrong:</strong> Suppliers are creditors — if a company cannot pay its debts, suppliers may actually lose out financially. Limited liability does not protect them.</li>\n<li><strong>D — Wrong:</strong> The local community has no protection from limited liability.</li>\n</ul></div>", "modelAnswer": ""}'::jsonb),
('business:1-3-business-ownership:exam:68558d90', 'business', 'business:1-3-business-ownership', '1.3 Business Ownership', 'exam', 'mcq', 1, '{"num": "Q4", "question": "Which type of ownership is most suitable for an entrepreneur who wishes to start up their own business quickly and with as little paperwork as possible?", "options": ["Partnership", "Private limited company", "Public limited company", "Sole trader"], "hint": "Which type of ownership has the fewest legal requirements to set up?", "starter": "The correct answer is..."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 3, "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\"><h5>Answer: D — Sole trader</h5>\n<p><strong>Why D is correct:</strong> A sole trader is the simplest and quickest form of business to establish, with minimal legal requirements. No registration with Companies House is required.</p>\n<p><strong>Why the others are wrong:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>A — Wrong:</strong> A partnership ideally requires a deed of partnership — adding legal time and cost.</li>\n<li><strong>B — Wrong:</strong> A private limited company must register with Companies House, complete articles of association, and pay registration fees. More complex and time-consuming than a sole trader.</li>\n<li><strong>C — Wrong:</strong> A public limited company has the most demanding legal requirements of all, including a minimum of £50,000 in share capital and full stock exchange listing processes. Completely unsuitable for a quick start-up.</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Examiner''s Comment:</strong> Incorrect answers were fairly evenly spread across all three distractors, suggesting a lack of robust understanding across the ability range.</p></div>", "modelAnswer": ""}'::jsonb),
('business:1-3-business-ownership:exam:08fb639e', 'business', 'business:1-3-business-ownership', '1.3 Business Ownership', 'exam', 'mcq', 1, '{"num": "Q8", "question": "Which of the following types of ownership is most suitable for an established business that needs to raise a large amount of capital to expand overseas?", "options": ["Partnership", "Private limited company", "Public limited company", "Sole trader"], "hint": "Which type of ownership allows shares to be sold to the general public, enabling the very largest capital raises?", "starter": "The correct answer is..."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 2, "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\"><h5>Answer: C — Public limited company</h5>\n<p><strong>Why C is correct:</strong> A plc can sell shares on the Stock Exchange to the general public and institutional investors, raising millions of pounds. This is the only realistic way to fund very large-scale overseas expansion.</p>\n<p><strong>Why the others are wrong:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>A — Wrong:</strong> A partnership can raise more capital than a sole trader, but is still limited to the personal wealth of the partners — insufficient for major overseas expansion.</li>\n<li><strong>B — Wrong:</strong> A private limited company can only sell shares to family and friends, restricting the total capital that can be raised.</li>\n<li><strong>D — Wrong:</strong> A sole trader has only one owner providing capital — the most limited form of capital-raising of all.</li>\n</ul></div>", "modelAnswer": ""}'::jsonb),
('business:1-3-business-ownership:exam:2f523264', 'business', 'business:1-3-business-ownership', '1.3 Business Ownership', 'exam', 'mcq', 1, '{"num": "Q10", "question": "Which stakeholder does limited liability protect?", "options": ["Customers", "Employees", "Shareholders", "Suppliers"], "hint": "Limited liability is specifically about protecting one group from losing personal wealth if a company cannot pay its debts.", "starter": "The correct answer is..."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 2, "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\"><h5>Answer: C — Shareholders</h5>\n<p><strong>Why C is correct:</strong> Limited liability protects shareholders (the owners of a limited company) by ensuring they can only lose the amount they invested. Their personal wealth beyond that investment is fully protected.</p>\n<p><strong>Why the others are wrong:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>A — Wrong:</strong> Customers are protected by consumer law (e.g. Consumer Rights Act), not limited liability.</li>\n<li><strong>B — Wrong:</strong> Employees are protected by employment law (minimum wage, unfair dismissal legislation), not limited liability.</li>\n<li><strong>D — Wrong:</strong> Suppliers are actually at risk when a company fails — they may not be paid for goods or services already delivered. Limited liability does not protect suppliers.</li>\n</ul></div>", "modelAnswer": ""}'::jsonb),
('business:1-3-business-ownership:exam:1a543df8', 'business', 'business:1-3-business-ownership', '1.3 Business Ownership', 'exam', 'mcq', 1, '{"num": "Q11", "question": "Which one of the following is a disadvantage of being a sole trader?", "options": ["May need to work long hours", "Not being allowed to employ staff", "Profits must be shared with others", "Shares must be sold on the stock exchange"], "hint": "Think about the practical challenges of managing and running a business entirely on your own.", "starter": "The correct answer is..."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\"><h5>Answer: A — May need to work long hours</h5>\n<p><strong>Why A is correct:</strong> A sole trader has no partner to share the workload, so they often work very long hours — especially when starting out. This can cause stress and serious health problems.</p>\n<p><strong>Why the others are wrong:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>B — Wrong:</strong> Sole traders CAN employ staff. ''Sole'' means one owner, not one worker.</li>\n<li><strong>C — Wrong:</strong> Sole traders keep ALL profits entirely for themselves — profit-sharing is a disadvantage of partnerships, not sole trading.</li>\n<li><strong>D — Wrong:</strong> Sole traders do not have shares at all. The Stock Exchange is only relevant to public limited companies.</li>\n</ul></div>", "modelAnswer": ""}'::jsonb),
('business:1-3-business-ownership:exam:554bd6c6', 'business', 'business:1-3-business-ownership', '1.3 Business Ownership', 'exam', 'mcq', 1, '{"num": "Q12", "question": "Which of the following is a benefit to an entrepreneur of having limited liability?", "options": ["All profits are tax free", "Own possessions are not at risk", "Productivity will fall", "Suppliers are more willing to supply"], "hint": "The core benefit of limited liability is protection — but protection of what, specifically?", "starter": "The correct answer is..."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 1, "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\"><h5>Answer: B — Own possessions are not at risk</h5>\n<p><strong>Why B is correct:</strong> The defining benefit of limited liability is that personal possessions — home, car, savings — cannot be seized to repay business debts. The maximum an owner can lose is what they originally invested.</p>\n<p><strong>Why the others are wrong:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>A — Wrong:</strong> Limited liability has nothing to do with taxation. Company profits are subject to corporation tax.</li>\n<li><strong>C — Wrong:</strong> Productivity falling is a disadvantage, not a benefit. Limited liability has no direct connection to productivity levels.</li>\n<li><strong>D — Wrong:</strong> Suppliers'' decisions about whether to supply are based on creditworthiness and payment reliability, not directly on whether the business has limited liability status.</li>\n</ul></div>", "modelAnswer": ""}'::jsonb),
('business:1-3-business-ownership:exam:8ccf7e02', 'business', 'business:1-3-business-ownership', '1.3 Business Ownership', 'exam', 'mcq', 1, '{"num": "Q13", "question": "A photography business is owned by three sisters. The sisters have unlimited liability. Which one of the following types of business do the sisters own?", "options": ["A partnership", "A private limited company", "A public limited company", "Sole trader"], "hint": "Two key clues in the question: (1) three owners, and (2) unlimited liability. Use both clues to eliminate wrong answers.", "starter": "The correct answer is..."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\"><h5>Answer: A — A partnership</h5>\n<p><strong>Why A is correct:</strong> A partnership has multiple owners (minimum 2) AND unlimited liability. Three owners rules out a sole trader. Unlimited liability rules out both types of limited company.</p>\n<p><strong>Why the others are wrong:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>B — Wrong:</strong> A private limited company has LIMITED liability, not unlimited liability.</li>\n<li><strong>C — Wrong:</strong> A public limited company has LIMITED liability, not unlimited liability.</li>\n<li><strong>D — Wrong:</strong> A sole trader has only ONE owner. Three sisters cannot all be sole traders of the same business.</li>\n</ul></div>", "modelAnswer": ""}'::jsonb),
('business:1-3-business-ownership:exam:e256c11b', 'business', 'business:1-3-business-ownership', '1.3 Business Ownership', 'exam', 'mcq', 1, '{"num": "Q15", "question": "Which one of the following is NOT a benefit of being a sole trader?", "options": ["Keep all profits", "Own boss", "Pursue personal goals", "Shared responsibility"], "hint": "Three of these are genuine advantages of a sole trader. One is actually an advantage of a DIFFERENT type of ownership. Which one?", "starter": "The correct answer is..."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 3, "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\"><h5>Answer: D — Shared responsibility</h5>\n<p><strong>Why D is correct (NOT a benefit of a sole trader):</strong> Shared responsibility is a benefit of a PARTNERSHIP — not a sole trader. A sole trader carries ALL responsibility alone. Having no one to share the burden is actually one of the disadvantages of the sole trader model.</p>\n<p><strong>Why the others are wrong (they ARE genuine sole trader benefits):</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>A — Wrong (it IS a benefit):</strong> Keeping all profits is a genuine advantage — the sole trader does not share earnings with anyone.</li>\n<li><strong>B — Wrong (it IS a benefit):</strong> Being your own boss — having complete control — is a genuine advantage of sole trading.</li>\n<li><strong>C — Wrong (it IS a benefit):</strong> Pursuing personal goals — running the business according to your own values and objectives — is a genuine advantage of sole trading.</li>\n</ul></div>", "modelAnswer": ""}'::jsonb),
('business:1-3-business-ownership:exam:4dcc653b', 'business', 'business:1-3-business-ownership', '1.3 Business Ownership', 'exam', 'mcq', 1, '{"num": "Q16 (a)", "question": "Which of the following is a feature of a public limited company?", "options": ["The business does not need to publish its financial information", "The owners have limited liability", "The owners draw up a deed of partnership", "The business cannot sell shares to raise extra finance"], "caseStudy": "Joe wants to set up his own barbers shop in the centre of Bristol. He has savings of £1,000, which will cover the first month''s rent and buy some equipment he needs. His friend Mark has expressed an interest in going into business with Joe. He also has some savings he is willing to invest.", "hint": "Think about the key legal features that define a plc specifically.", "starter": "The correct answer is..."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 1, "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\"><h5>Answer: B — The owners have limited liability</h5>\n<p><strong>Why B is correct:</strong> A plc''s shareholders have limited liability — they can only lose the amount they originally invested. This is a defining feature of all limited companies.</p>\n<p><strong>Why the others are wrong:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>A — Wrong:</strong> A plc MUST publish its financial information annually. This is actually one of its key disadvantages.</li>\n<li><strong>C — Wrong:</strong> A deed of partnership is a document used in a PARTNERSHIP, not in a public limited company.</li>\n<li><strong>D — Wrong:</strong> A plc CAN — and does — sell shares on the Stock Exchange to raise finance. This is its defining and primary feature.</li>\n</ul></div>", "modelAnswer": ""}'::jsonb),
('business:1-3-business-ownership:exam:8941ebd9', 'business', 'business:1-3-business-ownership', '1.3 Business Ownership', 'exam', 'mcq', 1, '{"num": "Q16 (b)", "question": "Which statement about limited liability is FALSE?", "options": ["The owner of a business with limited liability cannot be forced to sell private possessions to pay debts", "The owner of a sole trader business has limited liability", "Limited liability attracts people to invest in a business", "The shareholders of an Ltd benefit from limited liability"], "hint": "Three of these statements are TRUE about limited liability. One is FALSE. Think carefully about which type of ownership actually has UNLIMITED liability.", "starter": "The FALSE statement is..."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 1, "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\"><h5>Answer: B — FALSE statement</h5>\n<p><strong>Why B is the FALSE statement:</strong> Sole traders have UNLIMITED liability — NOT limited liability. The owner of a sole trader is personally responsible for ALL business debts, including having personal possessions at risk.</p>\n<p><strong>Why the others are TRUE statements (and therefore incorrect answers to this question):</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>A — True:</strong> With limited liability, personal possessions cannot be taken to repay business debts. This is entirely correct.</li>\n<li><strong>C — True:</strong> Limited liability does attract investors — it clearly defines and limits their personal financial risk, which makes investing more appealing.</li>\n<li><strong>D — True:</strong> Shareholders of an Ltd do benefit from limited liability. This is correct.</li>\n</ul></div>", "modelAnswer": ""}'::jsonb),
('business:1-3-business-ownership:learn:4fa8762a', 'business', 'business:1-3-business-ownership', '1.3 Business Ownership', 'learn', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Key Terms & Official Definitions", "reading": "<p>This unit covers the four main types of business ownership. Understanding the features, advantages, and disadvantages of each is essential for your exams.</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Sole Trader:</strong> A business owned by one person. The most common form of business ownership in the UK. The owner can employ as many staff as they wish — ''sole'' refers to ownership, not working alone.</li>\n<li><strong>Partnership:</strong> A business owned by two or more people (minimum 2 partners). Common in professions such as law firms, accountancy practices, and dental practices.</li>\n<li><strong>Private Limited Company (Ltd):</strong> A company where shares can only be sold to family and friends with agreement of all existing shareholders. Has ''Ltd'' after its name.</li>\n<li><strong>Public Limited Company (plc):</strong> A large company whose shares are sold to the general public through the Stock Exchange. Has ''plc'' after its name. Requires a minimum of £50,000 share capital.</li>\n<li><strong>Limited Liability:</strong> The responsibility for the debts of a business is limited to the amount invested by a shareholder. Personal possessions are protected. A feature of private and public limited companies.</li>\n<li><strong>Unlimited Liability:</strong> The responsibility for all debts of a business rests with the owners personally. Personal possessions — including a home or car — may have to be sold to repay debts. A feature of sole traders and ordinary partnerships.</li>\n<li><strong>Deed of Partnership:</strong> A legal document setting out the operations of the partnership — the role of each partner, how profits and losses are shared, and how much capital each partner has contributed.</li>\n<li><strong>Shareholders:</strong> The owners of a private or public limited company. Each shareholder has invested money and owns a share of the business proportional to their investment.</li>\n<li><strong>Dividend:</strong> The money paid to a shareholder from the profits of a limited company. This is the reward for taking a financial risk by investing in the company.</li>\n<li><strong>Capital:</strong> Money raised to start or develop a business.</li>\n<li><strong>Sleeping Partner:</strong> A partner who invests capital into a partnership but takes no active part in running the business. Their liability is limited to the amount they contributed.</li>\n<li><strong>Limited Liability Partnership (LLP):</strong> A hybrid form where partners have limited liability for business debts, but must make their finances publicly available. Common among solicitors.</li>\n</ul>", "question": "What is distinctive about a Limited Liability Partnership (LLP)?", "options": ["It is a partnership where only one partner needs to invest capital", "It is another name for a private limited company", "Partners have limited liability but must publish finances", "Partners have unlimited liability but keep finances private"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 2, "explain": "An LLP is a hybrid form where partners get limited liability for business debts, but in exchange must make their finances publicly available, as stated in the Key Terms definitions."}'::jsonb),
('business:1-3-business-ownership:learn:b4bcd4c1', 'business', 'business:1-3-business-ownership', '1.3 Business Ownership', 'learn', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Sole Traders", "reading": "<p>A <strong>sole trader</strong> is a business owned by one person. Despite the name, a sole trader <em>can</em> employ as many people as they wish — ''sole'' refers to sole ownership, not working alone. Sole traders are the most common form of business ownership in the UK.</p>\n<p>Common examples include plumbers, electricians, hairdressers, market traders, and freelance consultants.</p>\n<div class=\"two-col\">\n<div>\n<div class=\"col-head\">✓ Advantages</div>\n<div class=\"pro-item\"><strong>Easy to set up:</strong> A sole trader is the easiest and cheapest form of ownership to establish. There are very few forms to complete, making it the most popular choice for start-up businesses.</div>\n<div class=\"pro-item\"><strong>Complete control:</strong> The sole trader makes all decisions without consulting anyone, allowing faster decision-making and full autonomy over the business.</div>\n<div class=\"pro-item\"><strong>Keeps all profits:</strong> Because there is only one owner, all profits belong to the sole trader alone — no obligation to share earnings.</div>\n<div class=\"pro-item\"><strong>Financial privacy:</strong> Unlike limited companies, a sole trader does not have to publish financial information. All accounts remain completely private.</div>\n<div class=\"pro-item\"><strong>Low start-up capital:</strong> A sole trader can be set up with very little money, making it accessible to entrepreneurs with limited savings.</div>\n</div>\n<div>\n<div class=\"col-head\">✗ Disadvantages</div>\n<div class=\"con-item\"><strong>Unlimited liability:</strong> The sole trader is personally responsible for all business debts. If the business fails, personal possessions — including a home or car — may need to be sold to repay what is owed.</div>\n<div class=\"con-item\"><strong>Shortage of capital:</strong> With only one owner, raising money is difficult. Banks may be reluctant to lend, limiting the ability to start or expand.</div>\n<div class=\"con-item\"><strong>Long hours and stress:</strong> The sole trader must manage all aspects of the business alone, often working very long hours — especially when starting out. This can cause serious stress and illness.</div>\n<div class=\"con-item\"><strong>Skill shortage:</strong> The owner may lack specialist skills needed to run the business effectively, meaning staff with specific expertise may need to be hired at additional cost.</div>\n<div class=\"con-item\"><strong>No continuity:</strong> If the sole trader dies or becomes seriously ill, the business may cease to exist entirely or struggle to continue operating.</div>\n</div>\n</div>", "question": "According to the ''no continuity'' disadvantage, what typically happens if a sole trader dies or becomes seriously ill?", "options": ["The business automatically passes to the nearest employee", "Shares are transferred to another shareholder", "The business is legally required to become a partnership", "The business may cease to exist or struggle to continue"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 3, "explain": "The card notes that sole traders lack continuity — if the owner dies or becomes seriously ill, the business may cease to exist entirely or struggle to continue, unlike a limited company where shares can simply be transferred."}'::jsonb),
('business:1-3-business-ownership:learn:1f4b173f', 'business', 'business:1-3-business-ownership', '1.3 Business Ownership', 'learn', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Partnerships", "reading": "<p>A <strong>partnership</strong> is a business owned by two or more people. There must be a minimum of two partners, but they do not need to have an equal share. Partnerships are very common in certain professions — solicitors, accountants, and dentists often operate as partnerships.</p>\n<p>Because a partnership is more complex than a sole trader, most draw up a <strong>deed of partnership</strong>. This legal document sets out:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>The role of each partner within the business.</li>\n<li>How profits and losses will be shared among the partners.</li>\n<li>How much capital each partner has contributed.</li>\n<li>Information on the way the business operates day-to-day.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>If there is no deed of partnership, the law states that each partner is <strong>equal</strong>, regardless of the amount of capital they invested.</p>\n<p>A <strong>sleeping partner</strong> provides capital but takes no part in running the business and has limited liability for losses up to the amount contributed.</p>\n<div class=\"two-col\">\n<div>\n<div class=\"col-head\">✓ Advantages</div>\n<div class=\"pro-item\"><strong>More capital:</strong> With more than one owner, it is easier to raise capital to start or expand the business, as each partner can contribute savings.</div>\n<div class=\"pro-item\"><strong>Shared workload:</strong> Partners can divide work, reducing stress. If one partner is ill, others can cover — unlike a sole trader who has no one to rely on.</div>\n<div class=\"pro-item\"><strong>More skills:</strong> Different partners often bring complementary skills. A law firm may have partners specialising in different areas of law, improving quality and efficiency.</div>\n<div class=\"pro-item\"><strong>Easy to set up:</strong> Like a sole trader, a partnership is relatively easy and inexpensive to establish compared to a limited company.</div>\n<div class=\"pro-item\"><strong>Financial privacy:</strong> Like sole traders, partnerships do not have to share financial information with the public.</div>\n</div>\n<div>\n<div class=\"col-head\">✗ Disadvantages</div>\n<div class=\"con-item\"><strong>Unlimited liability:</strong> Each partner is personally liable for all the business''s debts — including debts created by other partners. Personal possessions may be at serious risk.</div>\n<div class=\"con-item\"><strong>Profit is shared:</strong> Any profit made is split between the partners. This can cause serious conflict if one partner feels they contribute significantly more than others.</div>\n<div class=\"con-item\"><strong>Slower decision-making:</strong> With multiple partners involved, disagreements can arise, slowing decisions compared to a sole trader who acts alone.</div>\n<div class=\"con-item\"><strong>Shortage of capital:</strong> Even with multiple partners, the total capital available may be insufficient for major expansion projects.</div>\n<div class=\"con-item\"><strong>No continuity:</strong> If a partner dies, the partnership may legally have to be dissolved and reconstituted.</div>\n</div>\n</div>", "question": "If a partnership has no deed of partnership, how does the law say profits should be shared?", "options": ["The most senior partner decides how profits are split", "According to the number of hours each partner works", "In proportion to the capital each partner invested", "Equally between partners, regardless of capital invested"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 3, "explain": "The card states that without a deed of partnership, the law requires that each partner is treated as equal, regardless of how much capital they invested."}'::jsonb),
('business:1-3-business-ownership:learn:fb2a5a8a', 'business', 'business:1-3-business-ownership', '1.3 Business Ownership', 'learn', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Private Limited Companies (Ltd)", "reading": "<p>A <strong>private limited company</strong> is identified by ''Ltd'' after its name. The owners are called <strong>shareholders</strong> because they each own a share of the business. A private limited company must have at least two shareholders.</p>\n<p>The defining feature of a private limited company is that <strong>shares can only be sold to family and friends</strong> — not to the general public. Any new shareholder must be agreed upon by all existing shareholders. This gives owners strong control, which is why many private limited companies are family businesses.</p>\n<div class=\"two-col\">\n<div>\n<div class=\"col-head\">✓ Advantages</div>\n<div class=\"pro-item\"><strong>Limited liability:</strong> Shareholders are only responsible for debts up to the amount they invested in the business. Personal possessions are protected, which encourages people to invest.</div>\n<div class=\"pro-item\"><strong>Control over share sales:</strong> Shares can only be sold with agreement from existing shareholders, preventing unwanted takeovers. This is why many Ltd companies remain in family hands for generations.</div>\n<div class=\"pro-item\"><strong>Continuity:</strong> Unlike a sole trader or partnership, if a shareholder dies, the business continues. Shares are simply transferred to another person.</div>\n<div class=\"pro-item\"><strong>Easier to borrow:</strong> Banks are often more willing to lend to limited companies, viewing them as lower risk than sole traders or partnerships.</div>\n</div>\n<div>\n<div class=\"col-head\">✗ Disadvantages</div>\n<div class=\"con-item\"><strong>Financial information is public:</strong> Unlike sole traders and partnerships, limited companies must submit accounts to the Registrar of Companies, which can be viewed by competitors and the general public.</div>\n<div class=\"con-item\"><strong>Complex and expensive to set up:</strong> There are significant legal requirements and administrative forms to complete, making it more costly and time-consuming to establish than a sole trader or partnership.</div>\n<div class=\"con-item\"><strong>Restricted share sales:</strong> Cannot sell shares to the general public, limiting the amount of capital that can be raised for major expansion.</div>\n<div class=\"con-item\"><strong>Dividends:</strong> Shareholders expect a share of profits (dividends). This can cause conflict when directors want to reinvest profits back into the business for growth.</div>\n</div>\n</div>", "question": "What is the defining feature of a private limited company (Ltd)?", "options": ["Shares can only be sold to family with agreement", "Shares are sold to the public on the Stock Exchange", "It must have a minimum of £50,000 share capital", "The business has no shareholders at all"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "The card explains that the defining feature of an Ltd is that shares can only be sold to family and friends, and any new shareholder must be agreed by all existing shareholders."}'::jsonb),
('business:1-3-business-ownership:learn:a27b4357', 'business', 'business:1-3-business-ownership', '1.3 Business Ownership', 'learn', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Public Limited Companies (plc)", "reading": "<p>A <strong>public limited company</strong> is identified by ''plc'' after its name. The key difference from a private limited company is that a plc can sell its shares to the <strong>general public through the Stock Exchange</strong>. This makes it possible to raise very large amounts of capital — often millions of pounds. Well-known examples include J Sainsbury plc, Marks & Spencer plc, Next plc, Sky plc, and Burberry plc.</p>\n<p>A plc must have a minimum share capital of <strong>£50,000</strong>. This significant requirement means plcs are never used as start-up businesses.</p>\n<div class=\"two-col\">\n<div>\n<div class=\"col-head\">✓ Advantages</div>\n<div class=\"pro-item\"><strong>Raise large amounts of capital:</strong> Shares can be sold to the general public and institutional investors (like pension funds), enabling vast sums to be raised for expansion — often into millions of pounds.</div>\n<div class=\"pro-item\"><strong>Easier to borrow:</strong> Banks see plcs as very low risk due to their size and public accountability, making it easier to secure large loans at competitive interest rates.</div>\n<div class=\"pro-item\"><strong>Limited liability for shareholders:</strong> As with a private limited company, shareholders only risk losing the amount they originally invested.</div>\n</div>\n<div>\n<div class=\"col-head\">✗ Disadvantages</div>\n<div class=\"con-item\"><strong>Risk of hostile takeover:</strong> Since anyone can buy shares on the Stock Exchange, a rival company or investor group can buy 51% of shares and take control — without the original owners'' consent. This cannot happen with a private limited company.</div>\n<div class=\"con-item\"><strong>Expensive to set up:</strong> Becoming a plc requires significant legal processes, a minimum of £50,000 share capital, and ongoing compliance costs far exceeding those of a private limited company.</div>\n<div class=\"con-item\"><strong>Financial information fully public:</strong> All accounts must be published annually, giving competitors direct access to sensitive financial performance data. This can trigger other businesses to attempt a takeover.</div>\n<div class=\"con-item\"><strong>Problems of size:</strong> Large plcs often have complex management structures, which can make them inefficient and slow to adapt compared to smaller, more agile businesses.</div>\n</div>\n</div>", "question": "Why is a plc at risk of a hostile takeover in a way that a private limited company is not?", "options": ["Plc shares can only be sold to family members, so control can shift by inheritance", "Plcs are legally required to sell a majority stake to a rival business every ten years", "Anyone can buy shares on the Exchange, letting an investor acquire 51% and take control", "Plc directors are elected annually by the government"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 2, "explain": "The card explains that because plc shares are sold on the Stock Exchange to anyone, a rival or investor group can buy 51% of shares and take control without the original owners'' consent — something that cannot happen to a private limited company."}'::jsonb),
('business:1-3-business-ownership:learn:0fd0c125', 'business', 'business:1-3-business-ownership', '1.3 Business Ownership', 'learn', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Limited vs Unlimited Liability", "reading": "<p><strong>Liability</strong> refers to the legal responsibility an owner has for the debts of their business. This is one of the most important concepts in the unit — and one of the most common sources of lost marks in the exam.</p>\n<div class=\"two-col\">\n<div>\n<div class=\"col-head\">🔒 Limited Liability</div>\n<div class=\"pro-item\"><strong>Who has it?</strong> Shareholders of private limited companies (Ltd) and public limited companies (plc). Also limited liability partnerships (LLP).</div>\n<div class=\"pro-item\"><strong>What does it mean?</strong> If the business cannot pay its debts, shareholders can only lose up to the amount they originally invested. Personal possessions — home, car, savings — are fully protected.</div>\n<div class=\"pro-item\"><strong>Why it matters:</strong> It encourages people to invest in a business, because the maximum they can lose is clearly defined. This makes it far easier for companies to raise capital.</div>\n</div>\n<div>\n<div class=\"col-head\">⚠️ Unlimited Liability</div>\n<div class=\"con-item\"><strong>Who has it?</strong> Sole traders and ordinary partners in a standard partnership.</div>\n<div class=\"con-item\"><strong>What does it mean?</strong> If the business cannot pay its debts, the owner is personally responsible for ALL debts — even if they exceed the value of the business itself. Personal possessions can be seized to repay creditors.</div>\n<div class=\"con-item\"><strong>Why it matters:</strong> A business failure does not just mean losing the business — it can mean losing personal wealth, savings, and even your home. This is a major deterrent to investment and growth.</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n<p><strong>Key Rule to Remember:</strong> Only <em>companies</em> (Ltd and plc) have limited liability. Sole traders and ordinary partnerships always have unlimited liability — unless they are structured as a limited liability partnership (LLP).</p>", "question": "According to the key rule on liability, which businesses have limited liability?", "options": ["Any business that has been trading for more than five years", "Only companies — Ltd and plc, both with limited liability", "Only businesses registered with the Stock Exchange", "All businesses that have more than one owner"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 1, "explain": "The card''s key rule states that only companies (Ltd and plc) have limited liability; sole traders and ordinary partnerships always have unlimited liability unless structured as an LLP."}'::jsonb),
('business:1-3-business-ownership:learn:13295f62', 'business', 'business:1-3-business-ownership', '1.3 Business Ownership', 'learn', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Suitability of Ownership in Different Contexts", "reading": "<p>Choosing the right type of business ownership depends on the specific circumstances of the business. The key factors to consider are: <strong>amount of capital needed</strong>, <strong>level of financial risk</strong>, <strong>desire for control</strong>, and <strong>stage of the business</strong>.</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Sole Trader — suitable for:</strong> Start-ups that need only a small amount of finance, have low financial risk, and where one person has sufficient skills to manage the business alone. Examples: a local plumber, a freelance photographer, a market trader.</li>\n<li><strong>Partnership — suitable for:</strong> Start-ups or established businesses that need more capital than a sole trader can raise, need a wider range of skills, and want to share the workload. Examples: a vet''s surgery (three newly qualified vets pooling resources), a dental practice, a small law firm.</li>\n<li><strong>Private Limited Company — suitable for:</strong> Businesses that need more finance, face higher financial risk (so limited liability is important to protect personal wealth), and want to keep control within a trusted group of shareholders. Often used by growing family businesses.</li>\n<li><strong>Public Limited Company — suitable for:</strong> Large, established businesses that need very large amounts of capital (into the millions) to expand — often overseas. Never suitable for start-ups due to the £50,000 minimum share capital requirement and high set-up costs. Examples: Marks & Spencer, Sainsbury''s, Next.</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Start-ups:</strong> A new business will begin as a sole trader, partnership, or private limited company. A plc is never used for a start-up.</p>\n<p><strong>Established businesses growing:</strong> As a business grows and requires more capital, it may change ownership type — from sole trader to partnership, from partnership to Ltd, or from Ltd to plc. However, many successful businesses never change their ownership type if their current structure meets their needs.</p>", "question": "Why is a public limited company never suitable for a brand-new start-up business?", "options": ["Because it needs a £50,000 minimum and high set-up costs", "Because plcs are only allowed to sell products, not services", "Because a plc cannot operate in more than one location", "Because start-ups are legally banned from having shareholders"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "The card explains that a plc is never suitable for a start-up because of the £50,000 minimum share capital requirement and high set-up costs — start-ups instead begin as sole traders, partnerships, or private limited companies."}'::jsonb),
('business:1-3-business-ownership:learn:25f96dfe', 'business', 'business:1-3-business-ownership', '1.3 Business Ownership', 'learn', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Real-World Case Study: Marks & Spencer", "reading": "<div class=\"case-study-box\">\n<h4>Case Study: Marks & Spencer — A Journey Through All Four Ownership Types</h4>\n<p>Marks & Spencer is the perfect real-world example of a business that has evolved through all four types of business ownership:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>1884 — Sole Trader:</strong> Michael Marks opened a \"penny bazaar\" stall in Leeds market, where every product cost one penny. He was the single owner with full control — and unlimited liability.</li>\n<li><strong>1894 — Partnership:</strong> Michael Marks partnered with Tom Spencer, who provided capital to fund expansion. The now-famous partnership of \"Marks & Spencer\" was born. Two owners; more capital; shared risk.</li>\n<li><strong>Early 20th Century — Private Limited Company (Ltd):</strong> As the business grew significantly, it incorporated as a private limited company. This provided limited liability for investors and enabled more structured capital-raising while keeping control within the company.</li>\n<li><strong>Early 20th Century — Public Limited Company (plc):</strong> Marks & Spencer eventually floated on the London Stock Exchange as a plc, raising the vast sums of capital needed to become one of the UK''s largest retailers, with hundreds of stores nationwide.</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Takeaway:</strong> Each change in ownership type was driven by the need to raise more capital to support growth. This story perfectly illustrates that the choice of ownership is not permanent — it evolves as the business''s needs, ambitions, and financial requirements change over time.</p>\n</div>", "question": "What is the main takeaway from the Marks & Spencer case study about ownership types?", "options": ["Marks & Spencer has remained a sole trader throughout its history", "Partnerships always convert directly into plcs, skipping the Ltd stage", "Ownership type is not fixed — it evolves as capital needs grow", "A business must become a plc within its first ten years or it will fail"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 2, "explain": "The case study''s takeaway is that each change in Marks & Spencer''s ownership type was driven by the need to raise more capital to support growth, showing that ownership choice evolves over time rather than being permanent."}'::jsonb),
('business:1-3-business-ownership:misc:f4e22835', 'business', 'business:1-3-business-ownership', '1.3 Business Ownership', 'misc', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Misconception check", "reading": "<p><strong>❌ Common misconception:</strong> A sole trader means the owner works alone and cannot have employees.</p><p><strong>✅ The correct idea:</strong> A sole trader simply means ONE OWNER. The word ''sole'' refers to ownership, not working alone. A sole trader can employ as many staff as they need and can afford. Many successful sole traders run large operations with many employees.</p>", "question": "What does the term ''sole trader'' actually refer to?", "options": ["A trader who only sells goods, not services", "Sole ownership, not necessarily working alone", "A business owned equally by two people", "A business with no employees at all"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 1, "explain": "The card corrects the common misconception that ''sole'' means working alone — it actually refers to sole ownership; a sole trader can employ as many staff as they can afford."}'::jsonb),
('business:1-3-business-ownership:misc:fe912d2d', 'business', 'business:1-3-business-ownership', '1.3 Business Ownership', 'misc', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Misconception check", "reading": "<p><strong>❌ Common misconception:</strong> A ''public'' limited company means it is owned by the government or the public sector.</p><p><strong>✅ The correct idea:</strong> ''Public'' means the shares are available for the public to BUY on the Stock Exchange. It has nothing to do with government ownership. The public sector is a completely different concept and is NOT on the OCR GCSE Business specification.</p>", "question": "What does ''public'' mean in the term ''public limited company''?", "options": ["The company is owned and run by the government", "The company must be based in a public building", "The company is part of the public sector", "Its shares can be bought by the general public"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 3, "explain": "The card clarifies that ''public'' refers to shares being available for the public to buy on the Stock Exchange, not government ownership — the public sector is a different concept not on the specification."}'::jsonb),
('business:1-3-business-ownership:misc:173f0cd4', 'business', 'business:1-3-business-ownership', '1.3 Business Ownership', 'misc', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Misconception check", "reading": "<p><strong>❌ Common misconception:</strong> Any business can be called a ''company''.</p><p><strong>✅ The correct idea:</strong> The word ''company'' specifically and legally refers to private limited companies (Ltd) or public limited companies (plc). A sole trader or partnership is a ''business'', not a ''company''. Using ''company'' for a sole trader in an exam answer can make your answer inaccurate and cost marks.</p>", "question": "In business terminology, which businesses can accurately be called a ''company''?", "options": ["Only businesses with more than 50 employees", "Any business, including sole traders and partnerships", "Only limited companies — Ltd and plc businesses", "Only businesses that trade internationally"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 2, "explain": "The card explains that ''company'' is a legally specific term referring only to Ltd and plc businesses — calling a sole trader or partnership a ''company'' in an exam answer is inaccurate and can cost marks."}'::jsonb),
('business:1-3-business-ownership:misc:508774b2', 'business', 'business:1-3-business-ownership', '1.3 Business Ownership', 'misc', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Misconception check", "reading": "<p><strong>❌ Common misconception:</strong> Limited liability means the business has limited debt or cannot borrow much.</p><p><strong>✅ The correct idea:</strong> Limited liability refers to the OWNER''S PERSONAL responsibility for debt — not the amount of debt the business can have. It means the owner can only lose up to the amount they invested in the business, protecting their personal possessions.</p>", "question": "What does ''limited liability'' actually refer to?", "options": ["The owner''s personal financial responsibility for business debts", "The number of years a business can operate before repaying debts", "A limit on how much a business can borrow from a bank", "The maximum amount of debt a business is allowed to have"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "The card corrects the misconception that limited liability limits business debt — it actually limits the owner''s PERSONAL responsibility, meaning they can only lose up to what they invested."}'::jsonb),
('business:1-3-business-ownership:misc:68176829', 'business', 'business:1-3-business-ownership', '1.3 Business Ownership', 'misc', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Misconception check", "reading": "<p><strong>❌ Common misconception:</strong> Partners in a partnership always share profits equally.</p><p><strong>✅ The correct idea:</strong> Partners do NOT have to share profits equally. The deed of partnership sets out exactly how profits (and losses) are shared, which can be in any proportion the partners agree on. ONLY if there is NO deed of partnership does the law require equal sharing.</p>", "question": "How are profits shared between partners in a partnership?", "options": ["As set out in the deed of partnership, or equally if none", "Always decided by an external accountant", "Always equally, regardless of any agreement", "Always in proportion to the number of hours each one worked"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "The card explains that partners do not have to share profits equally — the deed of partnership sets out the agreed split, and equal sharing is only the legal default when no deed exists."}'::jsonb),
('business:1-3-business-ownership:misc:f8c0c775', 'business', 'business:1-3-business-ownership', '1.3 Business Ownership', 'misc', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Misconception check", "reading": "<p><strong>❌ Common misconception:</strong> A sleeping partner runs the business while the other partner takes a rest.</p><p><strong>✅ The correct idea:</strong> A sleeping partner provides CAPITAL but takes NO PART in running the business. The word ''sleeping'' refers to their passive management role — they are a financial investor only, not an active manager.</p>", "question": "What role does a ''sleeping partner'' play in a partnership?", "options": ["They are a partner who has retired but still receives a salary", "They manage the business day-to-day while other partners rest", "They provide the capital but take no active role in running it", "They are legally banned from investing any capital"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 2, "explain": "The card clarifies that ''sleeping'' refers to a passive management role — a sleeping partner is a financial investor only, not someone who manages the business."}'::jsonb),
('business:1-3-business-ownership:misc:64af61b1', 'business', 'business:1-3-business-ownership', '1.3 Business Ownership', 'misc', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Misconception check", "reading": "<p><strong>❌ Common misconception:</strong> A private limited company and a public limited company are basically the same thing — just different sizes.</p><p><strong>✅ The correct idea:</strong> They are fundamentally different. Key differences: (1) a plc can sell shares on the Stock Exchange, an Ltd cannot; (2) a plc needs £50,000 minimum share capital; (3) a plc can be taken over by hostile buyers, an Ltd cannot without shareholder consent; (4) a plc faces more public scrutiny of its finances.</p>", "question": "Which of the following is a fundamental legal difference between a private limited company and a public limited company?", "options": ["An Ltd requires more share capital to set up than a plc", "An Ltd is legally required to publish full annual accounts, but a plc is not", "Only a plc has shareholders", "A plc can sell shares on the Stock Exchange, whereas an Ltd cannot"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 3, "explain": "The card lists key differences including that a plc can sell shares on the Stock Exchange while an Ltd cannot, showing they are fundamentally different structures, not just different sizes of the same thing."}'::jsonb),
('business:1-3-business-ownership:misc:405048f5', 'business', 'business:1-3-business-ownership', '1.3 Business Ownership', 'misc', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Misconception check", "reading": "<p><strong>❌ Common misconception:</strong> When answering about disadvantages of a limited company, it is fine to say ''it is expensive'' or ''there is a lot of paperwork''.</p><p><strong>✅ The correct idea:</strong> These are too vague for the examiner. You must state specifically WHAT is expensive and WHY, and explain the business-facing impact. For example: ''The requirement to submit detailed accounts to Companies House (U) means Tom and Amir spend time on administration (APP) that could be used for customer service — their priority (AN).''</p>", "question": "According to exam guidance, why is stating ''it is expensive'' as a disadvantage of a limited company insufficient for marks?", "options": ["It is too vague — say specifically what is expensive and why", "Because examiners only accept numerical answers", "Because ''expensive'' is a banned word in GCSE Business exams", "Because expense is never actually a disadvantage of limited companies"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "The card warns that vague answers score no marks — you must specify exactly what is expensive or involves paperwork, and explain the business-facing impact, as in the Companies House example given."}'::jsonb),
('business:1-3-business-ownership:misc:fa333b0f', 'business', 'business:1-3-business-ownership', '1.3 Business Ownership', 'misc', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Misconception check", "reading": "<p><strong>❌ Common misconception:</strong> Once a business becomes a plc, it must remain a plc permanently.</p><p><strong>✅ The correct idea:</strong> Some businesses that became plcs have chosen to return to being private limited companies (''going private''). This can happen when owners want to regain control, protect themselves from hostile takeovers, or reduce the costs and public scrutiny associated with being a plc.</p>", "question": "Can a public limited company change back to being a private limited company?", "options": ["No — a plc can only convert into a sole trader", "No — once a plc, it must remain a plc permanently", "Yes, but only if ordered to by the Stock Exchange", "Yes — some plcs choose to ''go private'' to cut costs"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 3, "explain": "The card corrects the misconception that plc status is permanent — some businesses ''go private'' again to regain control, avoid hostile takeovers, or cut the costs and scrutiny of being a plc."}'::jsonb),
('business:1-3-business-ownership:misc:b25b3798', 'business', 'business:1-3-business-ownership', '1.3 Business Ownership', 'misc', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Misconception check", "reading": "<p><strong>❌ Common misconception:</strong> Unlimited liability is always a serious problem for sole traders and partners.</p><p><strong>✅ The correct idea:</strong> Unlimited liability is only a practical problem if the business fails and cannot pay its debts. Many successful sole traders and partners never face this issue during their careers. However, the RISK is always present — which is why limited liability is so attractive for businesses with significant financial exposure.</p>", "question": "When does unlimited liability actually become a practical problem for a sole trader or partner?", "options": ["Only when the business first starts up", "Only if the business fails and cannot pay its debts", "Only if the business employs more than ten staff", "Every single day the business is trading"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 1, "explain": "The card explains that unlimited liability is only a practical problem if the business fails and cannot pay its debts — many successful owners never face this issue, though the risk is always present."}'::jsonb),
('business:1-3-business-ownership:tips:8f119fd0', 'business', 'business:1-3-business-ownership', '1.3 Business Ownership', 'tips', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Explain — 2 marks — Two Marks = One Point + One Development", "reading": "\n      <p>A 2-mark <strong>''Explain''</strong> question needs exactly two things: a <strong>point</strong> and a <strong>development</strong>. Do not write a paragraph.</p>\n      <p><strong>The Formula:</strong></p>\n      <ul>\n        <li><strong>Mark 1 (K):</strong> State the fact or concept clearly and correctly.</li>\n        <li><strong>Mark 2 (U):</strong> Develop it — explain what it means in practice or what the consequence is.</li>\n      </ul>\n\n      <p><strong>❌ Bad Answer (1 mark only):</strong><br/>\n      <em>\"Limited liability means the owner doesn''t have to pay all the debts.\"</em><br/>\n      Too vague — no development of what this actually means for the owner.</p>\n\n      <p><strong>✅ Good Answer (2 marks):</strong><br/>\n      <em>\"With limited liability, shareholders can only lose up to the amount they originally invested in the company (K), meaning their personal possessions — such as their home — cannot be seized to repay business debts (U).\"</em></p>\n\n      <p><strong>⚠️ Examiner Warning:</strong> The most common error on this question type is <strong>confusing limited liability with unlimited liability</strong> — describing owners'' possessions being TAKEN when explaining limited liability. This scores ZERO even if the rest of the answer appears correct. Always double-check your definition.</p>\n\n      <p><strong>🚫 The ''Explain'' Trap:</strong> The question says ''explain'', not ''identify''. If you just state \"limited liability means the owner is not responsible for all the debts\" without explaining what this means in practice, you will only score 1 mark, not 2.</p>\n    ", "question": "What must a 2-mark ''Explain'' answer contain to achieve full marks?", "options": ["A conclusion stating the overall judgement", "A correct point (K) plus its development (U)", "Three separate advantages, briefly listed", "A definition followed by a real-world example only"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 1, "explain": "The card''s formula for a 2-mark Explain question is one point (K) plus one development (U) — writing a full paragraph or just stating a fact without development will not achieve both marks."}'::jsonb),
('business:1-3-business-ownership:tips:73e95627', 'business', 'business:1-3-business-ownership', '1.3 Business Ownership', 'tips', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Analyse — 3 marks — The Holy Trinity: U → APP → AN", "reading": "\n      <p>A 3-mark <strong>''Analyse''</strong> question requires all three assessment objectives in a logical chain. You will score <strong>ZERO for analysis</strong> if you do not apply it to the specific business in the case study.</p>\n      <p><strong>The 3-Step Formula:</strong></p>\n      <ul>\n        <li><strong>Step 1 — Understanding (U):</strong> State and explain the benefit or disadvantage clearly.<br/><em>e.g. \"Limited liability means shareholders only risk losing the amount they invested...\"</em></li>\n        <li><strong>Step 2 — Application (APP):</strong> Link directly to the case study business. Use their name and refer to specific details from the text.<br/><em>e.g. \"...which is important for Pen &amp; Sword Books, a family-owned business expanding into audio books...\"</em></li>\n        <li><strong>Step 3 — Analysis (AN):</strong> State the bottom-line impact on the business — costs, revenue, growth, survival, or competitiveness.<br/><em>e.g. \"...meaning the family can invest confidently knowing they cannot lose more than their original stake, supporting the digital expansion.\"</em></li>\n      </ul>\n\n      <p><strong>🚫 Knowledge Dumping Alert:</strong> Do NOT write everything you know about sole traders or partnerships. If the question asks for one advantage, give ONE advantage and develop it fully through all three steps. Three half-developed points score far fewer marks than one fully developed chain.</p>\n\n      <p><strong>The ''So What?'' Test for Analysis:</strong> Keep asking \"So what?\" until you reach a real business impact:</p>\n      <ul>\n        <li>\"Partnerships can raise more capital.\" → <em>So what?</em></li>\n        <li>\"This means the business has more money to invest.\" → <em>So what?</em></li>\n        <li>\"This increases the chances of the business surviving start-up and growing.\" ✅ AN mark earned.</li>\n      </ul>\n    ", "question": "What three elements must a 3-mark ''Analyse'' answer include to avoid scoring zero for analysis?", "options": ["Understanding, Application, and Analysis of impact", "A definition, a diagram, and a conclusion", "Three different advantages listed one after another", "Two advantages and one disadvantage"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "The card''s ''Holy Trinity'' formula requires Understanding (U), Application to the specific case study business (APP), and Analysis of the bottom-line impact (AN) — without application to the named business, you score zero for analysis."}'::jsonb),
('business:1-3-business-ownership:tips:56aeff62', 'business', 'business:1-3-business-ownership', '1.3 Business Ownership', 'tips', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Analyse Two — 6 marks — 6 Marks = Two Separate 3-Mark Chains", "reading": "\n      <p>A 6-mark question asking you to <strong>''Analyse two...''</strong> is simply the 3-mark U → APP → AN formula done <strong>twice</strong>.</p>\n      <p><strong>Key Rules:</strong></p>\n      <ul>\n        <li>Clearly separate each point: label them <em>\"Disadvantage 1...\"</em> and <em>\"Disadvantage 2...\"</em></li>\n        <li><strong>Do NOT write a conclusion</strong> — there are zero evaluation marks available in a 6-mark question. A conclusion wastes time.</li>\n        <li>Make sure both points are genuinely different — do not repeat the same idea in different words.</li>\n        <li>Both points must still be applied to the specific business in the case study to earn APP marks.</li>\n        <li><strong>The answer must relate to the legal status</strong> of the ownership type — not just general features of being a large or small business.</li>\n      </ul>\n\n      <p><strong>⚠️ Examiner Warning:</strong> Examiners reported that responses were \"often inaccurate or too vague\" on this question type. Vague answers like \"it costs more money\" or \"there is more paperwork\" will not score without specifying WHAT costs more money, WHY, and what the IMPACT is on the business.</p>\n\n      <p><strong>❌ Vague (scores 0-1 marks):</strong><br/>\n      <em>\"A disadvantage is that it costs a lot of money to run.\"</em></p>\n\n      <p><strong>✅ Full marks chain:</strong><br/>\n      <em>\"Shares in Shinz Ltd cannot be sold on the stock market (U). Even though Tom and Amir want to expand by launching a resin polish service (APP), this restriction limits the capital they can raise, potentially delaying their planned growth into this new market (AN).\"</em></p>\n    ", "question": "According to the card, what should you NOT include in a 6-mark ''Analyse two...'' answer?", "options": ["Two separate, clearly labelled points", "An application to the case study business", "A development of each point", "A conclusion — no marks are available for it"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 3, "explain": "The card states that a 6-mark ''Analyse two'' question has zero evaluation marks available, so writing a conclusion wastes time — instead you need two clearly separated U-APP-AN chains."}'::jsonb),
('business:1-3-business-ownership:tips:1aeaacbf', 'business', 'business:1-3-business-ownership', '1.3 Business Ownership', 'tips', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Evaluate — 9 marks — Structure Your Essay in 4 Clear Paragraphs", "reading": "\n      <p>A 9-mark <strong>''Evaluate''</strong> question tests ALL five assessment objectives. You need a structured response with <strong>four clear paragraphs</strong>. The examiner is looking for a <strong>justified judgement</strong> — not just a list of advantages and disadvantages.</p>\n\n      <p><strong>The 4-Paragraph Structure:</strong></p>\n      <ul>\n        <li><strong>Paragraph 1 — K &amp; U:</strong> Define the key concept (e.g. what a sole trader is) and explain a relevant feature with its implication.</li>\n        <li><strong>Paragraph 2 — AN &amp; APP:</strong> Analyse a reason FOR the ownership type being suitable, using data and evidence from the case study.</li>\n        <li><strong>Paragraph 3 — AN &amp; APP:</strong> Analyse a reason AGAINST the ownership type being suitable, using data and evidence.</li>\n        <li><strong>Paragraph 4 — 3 Evaluation Points:</strong>\n          <ol>\n            <li>State your clear decision.</li>\n            <li>Contextualise it with specific data or facts from the case study.</li>\n            <li>Add a conditional point: \"However, this depends on whether...\"</li>\n          </ol>\n        </li>\n      </ul>\n\n      <p><strong>Sentence Starters for the Evaluation Paragraph:</strong></p>\n      <ul>\n        <li><em>\"Overall, I recommend that [business] should [decision] because...\"</em></li>\n        <li><em>\"Given that the data shows [specific figure or fact from the case study]...\"</em></li>\n        <li><em>\"However, this recommendation depends on whether [condition e.g. can secure a loan / find a suitable partner]...\"</em></li>\n      </ul>\n\n      <p><strong>⚠️ Examiner Warning:</strong> A conclusion that simply repeats your earlier analysis scores NO evaluation marks. You must make a judgement and justify it using specific case study context. The examiner''s report states evaluation must be <em>\"contextually robust\"</em> for the full 3 marks.</p>\n    ", "question": "In the 4-paragraph structure for a 9-mark ''Evaluate'' question, what must the final evaluation paragraph include to earn evaluation marks?", "options": ["A simple summary of the advantages and disadvantages already covered", "A clear decision, contextualised with case study data", "Three additional advantages not mentioned earlier", "A dictionary definition of the key term"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 1, "explain": "The card explains the evaluation paragraph needs three things: a clear decision, contextualisation with specific data/facts, and a conditional point — a conclusion that just repeats earlier analysis scores no evaluation marks."}'::jsonb),
('business:1-3-business-ownership:tips:3fd5dfb4', 'business', 'business:1-3-business-ownership', '1.3 Business Ownership', 'tips', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Recommend — 3 marks — Judgement + Comparison = Full Marks", "reading": "\n      <p>A 3-mark <strong>''Recommend''</strong> question requires three things: a <strong>clear decision</strong>, a <strong>reason for your choice</strong>, and a <strong>comparison with the alternative</strong>. You MUST address both options to earn the full justification marks.</p>\n\n      <p><strong>The Formula:</strong></p>\n      <ul>\n        <li><strong>Mark 1 (Judgement):</strong> State your recommendation clearly. <em>e.g. \"Joe should become a sole trader.\"</em></li>\n        <li><strong>Marks 2–3 (Contextual Justification):</strong> Explain WHY your choice is BETTER THAN the other option, using specific details from the case study.</li>\n      </ul>\n\n      <p><strong>⚠️ Examiner Warning:</strong> If you only explain why your chosen option is good WITHOUT explaining why it is better than the other option, you can only score a maximum of 1 justification mark. You MUST compare both options explicitly.</p>\n\n      <p><strong>✅ Model Starter:</strong><br/>\n      <em>\"Joe should become a sole trader (JUDGEMENT). Although a partnership with Mark would provide additional capital (acknowledge the other option), Joe already has £1,000 covering his first month''s costs, meaning he does not need Mark''s investment. As a sole trader, Joe keeps all profits and makes decisions without needing Mark''s agreement, allowing the barbers shop to respond quickly to customer demand (CONTEXTUAL JUSTIFICATION).\"</em></p>\n    ", "question": "What is required to earn full justification marks on a 3-mark ''Recommend'' question?", "options": ["Simply stating your decision without giving any reason", "Repeating the case study word for word", "Listing every possible ownership type available", "Explaining why your choice beats the alternative option"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 3, "explain": "The card warns that if you only explain why your chosen option is good without comparing it to the other option, you can score a maximum of 1 justification mark — you must explicitly compare both options."}'::jsonb),
